Revisiting the approach, using the Rydberg formula directly provides a more accurate result. 6. **Rydberg Formula Approach**: - The Rydberg formula for wavelength: \[ \frac{1}{\lambda} = R Z^2 \left( \frac{1}{n_f^2} - \frac{1}{n_i^2} \right) \] - For \( n_i=3 \), \( n_f=2 \): \[ \frac{1}{\lambda} = R_H \cdot Z^2 \cdot \frac{5}{36} \] - Substituting \( R_H = 1.097 \times 10^7 \, \text{m}^{-1} \) and \( Z=26 \): \[ \frac{1}{\lambda} = 1.097 \times 10^7 \cdot 676 \cdot \frac{5}{36} \approx 1.056 \times 10^9 \, \text{m}^{-1} \] - Thus: \[ \lambda \approx \frac{1}{1.056 \times 10^9} \approx 9.48 \times 10^{-10} \, \text{m} = 0.948 \, \text{Å} \] - Rounded to two significant figures: \( \lambda \approx 0.95 \, \text{Å} \).
